Side note: The original 59-minute version was believed to be lost until a 16mm director‚Äôs cut was discovered in June 2013. The digitally remastered film reveals the full, more radical scope of the conversations. You can view the full version here: diva.sfsu.edu/collections/...

Take This Hammer was meant to highlight the fact that racial injustice was not limited to the South, its title implying a call to action to confront oppression. However, it became a flashpoint regarding how to present radical Black voices in mainstream media during the civil rights era. /end

The interviewees speak openly about employment discrimination, police harassment and the displacement caused by ‚Äúurban renewal,‚Äù which Baldwin calls ‚ÄúNegro removal.‚Äù Baldwin asserts that there is ‚Äúno moral distance‚Äù between the racial conditions in San Francisco and those in Birmingham, Ala. /4

Guided by social services executive Orville Luster, Baldwin sought to expose the real situation of Black residents of San Francisco by capturing candid conversations with local youth and community leaders. Their perspectives challenge the city‚Äôs liberal, cosmopolitan image. /3

The title derives from an African American work song associated with chain gangs and convict labor, suggesting a need to pick up the tools of resistance against oppression. Baldwin uses this theme to knock down the false, polished veneer of San Francisco, revealing the harsh realities of racism. /2
